WEBVTT

00:58.391 --> 00:59.893
<i>...element of surprise is</i>

00:59.976 --> 01:01.644
<i>the only tactic Gordon
Brown has left.</i>

01:01.770 --> 01:03.521
<i>We'll be going live to Parliament.</i>

01:03.688 --> 01:07.192
<i>But first, more British troops
are being deployed to Afghanistan</i>

01:07.275 --> 01:08.985
<i>as part of the biggest
joint offensive...</i>

01:09.069 --> 01:10.862
<i>...since the 2001 invasion.</i>

01:11.529 --> 01:13.698
<i>The British Army's death toll
has already exceeded</i>

01:13.782 --> 01:15.825
<i>that of Iraq and the Falklands War,</i>

01:15.909 --> 01:17.869
<i>with those wounded
and requiring treatment at home</i>

01:17.952 --> 01:19.496
<i>also rising sharply.</i>

01:19.829 --> 01:21.790
<i>Fatalities have ris...</i>

01:36.846 --> 01:37.847
ID, please.

01:38.431 --> 01:39.849
I just popped into town.

01:45.605 --> 01:46.898
Private Shaw.

01:48.775 --> 01:50.110
Can you tell the young private
who I am?

01:50.193 --> 01:51.194
Sorry, ma'am.

01:51.277 --> 01:52.904
Increased security
with the deployment tonight.

01:54.406 --> 01:56.908
I'm sure the MOD's very interested
in the Colonel's supper.

02:04.791 --> 02:07.085
What are you doing?
Wake up, yeah?

02:07.544 --> 02:08.628
Do you realise who that was?

02:08.837 --> 02:09.921
Just get some wine.

02:11.423 --> 02:12.632
Hello.

02:14.551 --> 02:16.177
Do we have any olive oil?

02:16.636 --> 02:19.264
Erm... we have oil.

02:21.349 --> 02:22.350
Oh.

02:25.020 --> 02:26.938
I went all the way into town,
then forgot it.

02:29.274 --> 02:31.526
- Go ahead.
- Thank you, that's very kind.

02:32.485 --> 02:33.987
Erm... All right.

02:34.070 --> 02:37.532
Whole new world for you this time,
Lisa, Sergeant-Major's wife.

02:37.657 --> 02:40.702
- Congratulations on the promotion.
- Thank you very much.

02:41.703 --> 02:44.414
Lots of new responsibilities for you
with the wives.

02:44.497 --> 02:45.498
Yeah.

02:45.582 --> 02:48.084
I'm sure you've got lots of ideas
up your sleeve.

02:48.543 --> 02:51.338
- Oh, yeah.
- Planning is key.

02:51.421 --> 02:53.214
OK, well, thank you for the advice.

02:53.590 --> 02:54.632
Any time.

03:22.494 --> 03:23.536
You not done yet?

03:24.412 --> 03:25.830
Grace came over to say goodbye.

03:25.914 --> 03:28.958
- Oh, right. Where's she going?
- To live with her aunt off base.

03:29.501 --> 03:31.086
And have a life.

03:31.753 --> 03:34.589
There are positives
to being surrounded by people

03:34.673 --> 03:35.799
who are in the same boat as you.

03:35.882 --> 03:37.300
Mum, please don't.

03:39.386 --> 03:41.638
By the left! Left wheel!

03:49.437 --> 03:52.065
<i>He's coming
to get him. Rargh!</i>

03:53.858 --> 03:56.027
<i>Come on, Billy, story
time. Come on.</i>

03:57.112 --> 03:59.197
<i>Are you going
away tomorrow?</i>

03:59.447 --> 04:02.325
<i>I am, but only for a little bit,
though, OK?</i>

04:02.909 --> 04:05.787
<i>Who's gonna read stories
when you're away?</i>

04:13.712 --> 04:15.880
Oh, God, why are you so clumsy?

04:15.964 --> 04:19.342
Maybe this is God's way of telling
us to put it in a frame.

04:19.426 --> 04:22.220
- No, I like it on the fridge.
- It'd be better protected under glass.

04:22.303 --> 04:24.055
It would be frozen and formal.

04:24.139 --> 04:26.725
I prefer it where it lives,
on the fridge,

04:27.350 --> 04:30.645
in amongst my postcards
and my shopping lists and all my...

04:32.355 --> 04:33.565
my everyday things.

04:33.898 --> 04:35.775
Jamie always hated that photo.

04:35.984 --> 04:38.820
Said it made him look like
an American talk show host.

04:40.196 --> 04:41.197
Well, I like it.

04:45.785 --> 04:47.495
- Fine.
- Fine.

04:56.296 --> 04:58.548
Are you going to be
OK when I'm gone?

04:58.631 --> 04:59.674
Mm.

04:59.758 --> 05:02.010
I'll be fine. Of course I will.

05:02.093 --> 05:04.512
I mean, it's my fifth
tour.

05:05.055 --> 05:08.641
Yeah, but things are
completely different this time.

05:14.230 --> 05:18.360
Do you know? I think I'm going to
offer my help in supporting the wives.

05:18.943 --> 05:21.654
I don't trust that Lisa,
the new RSM's wife.

05:21.738 --> 05:23.782
She's very cavalier
about the whole thing.

05:23.865 --> 05:25.867
- I'm sure she has a plan.
- Mm.

05:27.911 --> 05:31.164
Not that she won't appreciate
your support as well.

05:36.252 --> 05:38.546
Look after Mummy.
If she gets upset, give her a hug.

05:38.963 --> 05:40.632
- I will.
- OK, good boy.

05:41.174 --> 05:43.760
This is gonna keep you safe
while I'm away.

05:44.636 --> 05:46.096
Just like mine'll keep me safe.

05:49.015 --> 05:50.016
Right, kids.

05:50.975 --> 05:52.769
OK, remember what
we do with this?

05:53.561 --> 05:55.855
- Cross it off every day.
- Yeah, until?

05:56.147 --> 05:58.525
- Daddy's home.
- And we are?

05:58.733 --> 05:59.776
- Chuffed.
- Chuffed.

05:59.859 --> 06:01.111
Chuffed, yeah.

06:28.847 --> 06:30.598
Yeah, I know.

06:33.601 --> 06:35.020
Check out the blast boxers.

06:37.230 --> 06:39.566
- Not funny, Red.
- What? They're Kevlar.

06:40.316 --> 06:42.610
I'm just protecting the family jewels
for your pleasure.

06:42.777 --> 06:44.696
- Who's she talking to?
- I don't know.

06:45.530 --> 06:47.198
Better not be talking to those lads.

06:47.991 --> 06:50.076
- I was a lad once, remember?
- Yeah, thanks.

06:50.618 --> 06:51.703
That's really helpful.

06:52.620 --> 06:53.663
Is that my razor?

06:54.831 --> 06:57.125
Are you packing my stuff up again
before I've left?

06:57.292 --> 06:58.293
No.

06:58.710 --> 07:00.837
Well, I'm taking this.

07:01.004 --> 07:03.381
- Why? You're not gonna read it.
- I am. It's about leadership.

07:03.882 --> 07:06.593
Fine. Last time you took
<i>War And Peace,</i>

07:06.676 --> 07:11.348
spent your whole time reading <i>Heat</i>
magazine and watching romcoms.

07:12.974 --> 07:13.975
Are you angry?

07:14.059 --> 07:16.102
No, I don't give a
shit what you read.

07:16.269 --> 07:19.230
I'm just getting ready for another
six months as a single mother.

07:20.357 --> 07:21.358
All right?

07:23.193 --> 07:25.403
There, you can
forget about me now.

07:31.242 --> 07:32.243
Just get off.

07:35.163 --> 07:36.289
Get off!

07:38.792 --> 07:39.918
Do you really want me to?

07:47.884 --> 07:48.885
No.

07:59.521 --> 08:00.689
Oh, shit!

08:09.489 --> 08:11.324
Yes.

08:13.785 --> 08:14.911
Listen, I've got to go.

08:15.161 --> 08:17.580
Yeah, OK, I'll speak to you later.
Bye-bye.

08:22.460 --> 08:23.461
You better write to me.

08:23.670 --> 08:25.755
And I mean proper letters,
not just emails.

08:30.010 --> 08:31.219
Come here.

08:50.155 --> 08:52.240
They've stopped doing
the jumbo crossword in the paper

08:52.323 --> 08:53.867
so I printed it off the net.

08:57.328 --> 08:58.329
No crossword?

09:01.458 --> 09:02.500
I've got to go.

09:04.336 --> 09:05.420
Right.

09:39.746 --> 09:40.747
Oh.

09:41.373 --> 09:42.999
- Hi, Kate.
- Hello, Lisa.

09:44.209 --> 09:46.211
I'm late for a meeting
with Crooks.

09:47.045 --> 09:49.839
- Forgot the clocks went forward.
- Oh.

09:50.674 --> 09:51.675
Well, don't worry about it.

09:51.758 --> 09:52.926
The Brigadier's
still in there with him.

09:53.009 --> 09:54.719
Oh, great. Great.

09:57.972 --> 09:58.973
Quite right.

09:59.391 --> 10:01.601
I imagine the spouses
are quite anxious.

10:01.726 --> 10:03.561
We all know what
to expect this time.

10:03.645 --> 10:06.147
- Who's your point person?
- Lisa Lawson is the RSM's wife, sir.

10:06.231 --> 10:08.483
She wasn't too chuffed to get the
job but I think she'll rise to it.

10:08.566 --> 10:10.402
These things don't
happen overnight.

10:11.027 --> 10:13.446
And Kate Barclay will help
with the pastoral care.

10:13.613 --> 10:15.824
- Kate will?
- Yes, sir. She volunteered.

10:15.907 --> 10:19.494
I think after losing Jamie on the last
tour, she's keen to keep occupied.

10:19.577 --> 10:21.329
Sorry to interrupt.

10:21.413 --> 10:23.415
- Kate.
- Hello, Jeremy.

10:23.748 --> 10:25.875
The Brigadier and I were
discussing the new welfare directives.

10:25.959 --> 10:28.128
Social activities,
getting the women on board.

10:28.211 --> 10:30.880
Top brass telling us what to do.

10:30.964 --> 10:32.882
I think I should leave you to it.

10:40.265 --> 10:42.434
- Oh...
- No, that's all right.

10:43.560 --> 10:44.561
Got it.

10:45.770 --> 10:48.148
Colonel Barclay's wife would like
to take a more active role

10:48.231 --> 10:50.150
in supporting the spouses
during this deployment.

10:50.233 --> 10:51.401
Oh!

10:52.193 --> 10:54.404
I know it's not customary
for the Colonel's wife

10:54.487 --> 10:55.905
to get her hands dirty...

10:55.989 --> 10:57.449
Yeah, exactly. That's my role.

10:57.532 --> 10:58.783
No, of course. Of course.

11:01.036 --> 11:05.540
So, erm... what do you have in
store in terms of social activities?

11:08.376 --> 11:09.836
Well, we have our coffee mornings.

11:10.670 --> 11:11.755
Coffee mornings, yeah.

11:12.005 --> 11:13.048
And?

11:16.176 --> 11:17.469
Pot luck parties.

11:17.552 --> 11:19.262
Oh, pot luck party?

11:19.679 --> 11:21.598
That's when everyone brings a dish
and gets drunk.

11:23.099 --> 11:24.434
Of course, we've got
my walk on the moors.

11:24.517 --> 11:28.021
With the greatest respect, Kate,
most women don't have a mess to drink in.

11:28.438 --> 11:30.023
They can't go into
town and get pissed

11:30.106 --> 11:31.941
so they need somewhere
to let off steam.

11:32.108 --> 11:33.360
- Absolutely.
- Yeah.

11:33.693 --> 11:34.694
Absolutely.

11:36.029 --> 11:38.823
Erm... so, anything else?

11:42.118 --> 11:45.538
Why don't we just brainstorm with
the women at the next coffee morning?

11:49.501 --> 11:50.669
Go and have a play, Bills.

11:52.545 --> 11:55.173
You can bring whatever
cakes you want.

11:56.174 --> 11:57.967
I'll just introduce you
to Annie and Helen.

11:58.093 --> 12:00.428
This is Sarah, Private
Wheeler's wife.

12:00.512 --> 12:02.722
- Just marched in yesterday.
- Are you settling in?

12:02.806 --> 12:06.559
Fine, yeah, except everyone
keeps asking me what rank I am.

12:06.643 --> 12:09.646
What the hell is that? They look like
squashed little turds.

12:10.772 --> 12:13.358
I think it's, erm...
Kate's contribution.

12:13.441 --> 12:16.361
Lisa seems to be running late.

12:16.444 --> 12:19.906
- She's here.
- Hey.

12:19.989 --> 12:21.408
Oh, I'm sorry.

12:22.534 --> 12:24.786
- Would you like to come to the front?
- No, you're grand.

12:25.203 --> 12:26.579
You don't want to kick things off?

12:27.247 --> 12:28.456
Well, it has kicked off.

12:31.167 --> 12:33.128
What do people do
in these coffee mornings?

12:33.211 --> 12:35.672
I think they just... drink coffee.

12:39.926 --> 12:41.177
Sorry, everyone. Hello.

12:41.553 --> 12:45.098
If you'd all like to gather round
and take a seat.

12:45.223 --> 12:48.393
There's no need to be shy.
Front row's nice and empty.

12:48.518 --> 12:50.395
So, some of you don't know me.

12:51.062 --> 12:53.773
I'm Kate Barclay,
Colonel Barclay's wife.

12:54.607 --> 12:58.278
Today we need to come up with
some exciting activities and pursuits

12:58.403 --> 13:01.656
for us to do
while our service people are away.

13:01.948 --> 13:03.033
So, shall we start?

13:04.159 --> 13:06.536
Erm... Lisa? Lisa? Lisa?

13:07.871 --> 13:09.706
Do you think you could write things
on the board for me?

13:10.498 --> 13:11.541
Thank you.

13:15.253 --> 13:16.296
So...

13:17.172 --> 13:21.009
I thought we could have
a formal dinner once a month

13:21.092 --> 13:23.595
to explore all aspects
of global cuisine.

13:27.807 --> 13:30.727
Then perhaps the film night
could become a film season

13:30.810 --> 13:32.937
where we could examine
the body of an auteur

13:33.063 --> 13:35.982
and would provide an educational
aspect to leisure pursuits

13:36.066 --> 13:37.317
in a non-alcoholic environment.

13:37.400 --> 13:39.069
Non-alcoholic environment?

13:40.320 --> 13:42.197
- What's the matter?
- No, no.

13:42.280 --> 13:44.324
It's just in general,
when we watch films,

13:44.741 --> 13:47.619
you know,
usually we like them to be... fun.

13:47.702 --> 13:50.413
Perhaps open the ideas to the room?

13:50.663 --> 13:51.664
Yeah.

13:52.415 --> 13:55.627
Well, we did a book
club in Germany.

13:55.752 --> 13:57.253
Book club, great, great. Super.

13:57.337 --> 13:59.172
What about a footie club?

13:59.255 --> 14:02.425
We had a cracking five-a-side
in Aldershot, it was something else.

14:02.884 --> 14:04.511
Football! Yes, why not?

14:04.678 --> 14:07.222
- Start a needlework club.
- Needlework, right.

14:07.305 --> 14:09.224
Baking or bread-making.

14:09.307 --> 14:12.060
Yeah. Yeah, and then we could
collect alms for the poor

14:12.143 --> 14:14.062
and do a bit of basket weaving.

14:15.355 --> 14:17.065
It's all a bit <i>Little Women,</i> isn't it?

14:17.148 --> 14:19.192
Let's just get the strippers in.

14:19.317 --> 14:21.986
Give the rear party soldiers a case
of beer and have a Mr World contest.

14:22.070 --> 14:23.780
That'd be very entertaining.

14:25.407 --> 14:28.368
But, actually, right now,
we're looking for clubs to join.

14:29.536 --> 14:30.578
What about singing?

14:30.704 --> 14:31.788
Singing?

14:32.122 --> 14:34.916
My bridesmaids did <i>Angels</i> by
Robbie at my wedding.

14:35.458 --> 14:36.918
It was amazing.

14:38.044 --> 14:40.463
OK, erm... yeah. Super.

14:40.964 --> 14:44.884
A choir. Has anyone had any
experience of running a choir?

14:45.051 --> 14:47.929
Lisa, you're musical, no?

14:48.013 --> 14:51.641
No, my mum used to teach music.

14:51.725 --> 14:53.435
But, I mean,
choir's not really my thing.

14:53.685 --> 14:54.686
Right.

14:56.980 --> 14:57.981
Knitting?

14:59.315 --> 15:00.316
Knitting?

15:00.984 --> 15:01.985
Knitting.

15:08.742 --> 15:10.118
Should we have invited Kate?

15:10.827 --> 15:12.037
I bet you she can knit.

15:17.042 --> 15:18.043
Ohh.

15:18.126 --> 15:20.754
You know this is supposed to
take your mind off being upset?

15:21.254 --> 15:24.257
I just... I wanted to make
something nice for Liam.

15:24.341 --> 15:26.760
I love wool, I love sheep.

15:26.885 --> 15:28.595
Any little mistakes
give knitting character.

15:29.346 --> 15:30.347
Let's have a look.

15:34.476 --> 15:37.520
There you go, make a lovely...
tea cosy.

15:37.604 --> 15:41.066
- Or toilet roll cover.
- Cos we all need one of those.

15:41.316 --> 15:44.194
I don't know how you lot
can just makes jokes.

15:44.819 --> 15:46.154
I just feel sick all the time.

15:46.237 --> 15:49.407
Every time the phone rings,
every time the doorbell goes.

15:50.575 --> 15:52.035
I feel sick. How do you cope?

15:55.830 --> 15:57.624
Do you not... talk about it?

16:01.127 --> 16:03.129
- Who wants some wine?
- I'd love some wine.

16:04.798 --> 16:07.926
- Lisa, where are your glasses?
- In the dishwasher.

16:09.427 --> 16:11.429
All right, Frankie? Give us a smile!

16:11.763 --> 16:12.764
There you go.

16:15.058 --> 16:16.059
What?

16:22.732 --> 16:24.401
There are some benefits
when they go away.

16:24.943 --> 16:26.152
I grow my pubes.

16:26.444 --> 16:28.738
It's like Sherwood Forest
by the time Matt gets home.

16:31.324 --> 16:32.784
And you don't have to
brush your teeth.

16:33.535 --> 16:35.495
You don't have to pretend
you like <i>Top Gear.</i>

16:39.833 --> 16:41.418
<i>Today we're gonna
be making some tea,</i>

16:41.501 --> 16:43.878
<i>and taking a look at
the Brexar glass kettle.</i>

16:44.629 --> 16:48.425
<i>For today only, if you
purchase the Brexar glass kettle,</i>

16:48.508 --> 16:53.138
<i>you also get this stunning five-piece
knife set and wooden block.</i>

16:53.221 --> 16:56.349
<i>So clever and unique.
It's the Brexar glass kettle.</i>

16:56.433 --> 16:58.601
<i>It takes tea-making
to a whole new level.</i>

17:15.744 --> 17:17.287
- Yeah?
- <i>Hello, Kate.</i>

17:17.370 --> 17:20.248
<i>Comms are down.
No further details at this time.</i>

17:21.374 --> 17:22.625
But they've only just got there.

17:22.709 --> 17:24.461
<i>Sat phone and
internet on lockdown.</i>

17:24.544 --> 17:26.588
<i>I'll let you know when I hear further.</i>

17:26.671 --> 17:27.672
Yeah.

17:34.721 --> 17:36.056
- Hello.
- Hiya.

17:36.139 --> 17:37.974
- Is your mum in?
- Mum?

17:40.518 --> 17:42.062
So... how was knitting club?

17:42.604 --> 17:45.065
- There isn't a knitting club.
- Yes, I've heard the joke.

17:45.357 --> 17:47.650
First rule of knitting club:
"There is no knitting club."

17:47.734 --> 17:51.363
They disbanded last night
due to impracticalities.

17:51.613 --> 17:52.697
Oh.

17:54.866 --> 17:56.785
- They can't knit.
- Oh.

17:57.911 --> 17:58.912
Hi.

17:59.079 --> 18:00.497
Get a move on,
you're gonna be late.

18:02.082 --> 18:03.166
Yeah?

18:04.084 --> 18:05.085
Comms are down.

18:08.254 --> 18:10.006
- What, already?
- They're stuck in Green Zone.

18:10.090 --> 18:13.343
- They've got to tab out.
- Do the women know?

18:13.760 --> 18:15.345
A text message has gone out.

18:15.804 --> 18:16.971
Best thing is to keep busy.

18:24.437 --> 18:26.523
<i>...possible bypass routes.</i>

18:26.606 --> 18:28.733
<i>We see first-hand for ourselves.</i>

18:28.817 --> 18:32.946
<i>While we're filming, a report comes in
of another bombing close to the base.</i>

18:33.029 --> 18:36.241
<i>The Yorks Quick Reaction Force
gets ready to move out.</i>

18:36.324 --> 18:37.325
You all right?

18:37.409 --> 18:40.036
<i>Just been scrambled
because a suicide bomber</i>

18:40.120 --> 18:42.205
- <i>has just detonated his device...</i>
- Thank you.

18:44.207 --> 18:45.417
Gonna look good.

18:48.003 --> 18:49.170
Sorry.

18:51.923 --> 18:53.049
Hello?

18:54.342 --> 18:55.802
No, I've not been in an accident.

19:21.077 --> 19:22.662
- Hello.
- Hi.

19:22.912 --> 19:24.539
I just thought I'd pop in
and see how you're doing.

19:25.540 --> 19:27.459
Oh, OK. Thank you.

19:27.542 --> 19:28.668
Erm...

19:29.627 --> 19:33.298
Richard and I were also married
last minute, pre-deployment.

19:33.381 --> 19:36.384
My family all thought I was
pregnant, just being coy.

19:39.637 --> 19:40.638
Oh, are you?

19:41.473 --> 19:44.059
No, Liam just wanted me
to be next of kin.

19:44.976 --> 19:48.021
You know, comms down
doesn't necessarily mean anything.

19:48.104 --> 19:50.065
It's just the men
aren't allowed to talk to us.

19:50.774 --> 19:54.110
The military want to ensure that
no false information gets through.

19:54.819 --> 19:56.654
It's very important to keep busy.

19:57.489 --> 19:58.782
Less time to think about things.

19:59.991 --> 20:00.992
Yeah.

20:01.743 --> 20:03.370
I was actually thinking
of decorating.

20:03.870 --> 20:04.871
Hm.

20:04.954 --> 20:07.665
It is a bit depressing, isn't it,
the magnolia box?

20:09.417 --> 20:11.878
I was gonna do a, erm...

20:12.462 --> 20:13.713
a signature wall.

20:14.339 --> 20:17.425
And then pick out the purple
in the other walls.

20:17.509 --> 20:20.136
Yeah, hm... it's a bit signature.

20:20.261 --> 20:22.180
It took Richard and I
six coats of paint

20:22.263 --> 20:25.141
to cover up the mess I made
when we first marched out.

20:27.310 --> 20:29.521
Oh, God, sorry, that's Liam.

20:29.604 --> 20:32.232
He always puts our teddies
into different sexual positions,

20:32.315 --> 20:33.692
every time I leave the room.

20:33.775 --> 20:35.860
It's to make me laugh,
he's done it since we were kids.

20:35.944 --> 20:39.072
Not "kids" kids, since we were 15.

20:40.615 --> 20:42.367
Let's get cracking on these boxes,
shall we?

20:42.450 --> 20:44.619
I've got this exercise bike
I need to finish.

20:44.703 --> 20:47.122
OK, great.

20:59.342 --> 21:00.844
Comms back on is a good thing!

21:00.927 --> 21:03.179
Mm, yeah, I know. Sorry.

21:03.388 --> 21:04.723
Aww!

21:05.432 --> 21:06.808
Come on.

21:08.685 --> 21:09.936
Don't be silly.

21:10.645 --> 21:12.897
Let's get some music on
and get cracking, eh?

21:19.696 --> 21:20.697
Sorry.

21:21.614 --> 21:22.657
Thanks.

21:29.622 --> 21:30.915
What have we got here?

21:32.250 --> 21:33.251
Erm...

21:37.922 --> 21:40.008
Probably just start
with the instructions.

21:40.759 --> 21:42.052
- Here you go.
- Let's have a look.

21:45.013 --> 21:48.850
<i>Sprung in completeness</i>

21:48.975 --> 21:50.685
<i>Where His feet...</i>

21:57.067 --> 21:59.736
Just give one of those to everyone.
There should be enough.

22:03.114 --> 22:04.115
What you doing?

22:05.492 --> 22:07.827
Right, has everyone
got a hymn sheet?

22:08.370 --> 22:10.622
- Time to liven up this coffee morning.
- What's happening?

22:11.414 --> 22:12.999
I'm going to give you all a note.

22:13.083 --> 22:16.461
Then I'm going to count to three
and we can start. So...

22:18.129 --> 22:22.759
<i>La-la-la-la-la-la</i>

22:22.842 --> 22:24.302
One, two, three...

22:24.386 --> 22:28.723
<i>Morning has broken</i>

22:28.807 --> 22:30.308
<i>Like the...</i>

22:31.601 --> 22:33.436
Okay, I'll just... Everyone up.

22:33.520 --> 22:34.521
Come on, up your get.

22:34.813 --> 22:35.897
I'll start again.

22:37.232 --> 22:38.858
One, two, three...

22:38.942 --> 22:42.779
<i>Morning has broken</i>

22:42.862 --> 22:46.741
<i>Like the first morning</i>

22:46.825 --> 22:50.412
<i>Blackbird has spoken</i>

22:50.495 --> 22:53.998
<i>Like the first bird</i>

22:56.793 --> 22:57.961
<i>Prai...</i>

22:59.254 --> 23:01.006
OK, I'll just give you the note again.

23:01.089 --> 23:03.008
<i>La-la-la-la-la</i>

23:03.842 --> 23:05.301
One, two, three...

23:05.385 --> 23:09.014
<i>Praise for the singing</i>

23:09.097 --> 23:12.600
<i>Praise for the morning</i>

23:13.059 --> 23:17.564
<i>Praise
for the singing...</i>

23:17.647 --> 23:18.982
<i>Fresh from the...</i>

23:19.065 --> 23:20.483
Billy. Sorry.

23:20.567 --> 23:22.027
<i>...world</i>

23:22.110 --> 23:24.320
That's... That's lovely.
That was lovely.

23:24.404 --> 23:26.781
I've got to run to work. Sorry. Sorry.

23:27.782 --> 23:28.825
Bye.

23:28.908 --> 23:30.201
I was really enjoying that.

23:31.369 --> 23:33.204
- Lisa, wait.
- Why?

23:33.872 --> 23:36.291
That was like the incantations
of a bunch of witches.

23:36.374 --> 23:38.293
- Bit dramatic.
- No, it's an understatement.

23:38.376 --> 23:40.128
That was horrible.

23:40.211 --> 23:41.880
They need something to focus on.

23:42.589 --> 23:43.965
I think Afghan is enough.

23:44.049 --> 23:48.511
No, besides that. They need
something to work on collectively,

23:48.595 --> 23:50.972
a project,
something that brings them together.

23:51.056 --> 23:54.559
Look, if you think singing
<i>Onward, Christian Soldiers</i>

23:54.642 --> 23:56.603
with a pole up your arse
is what the women need,

23:56.686 --> 23:58.063
you're more out of touch
than I thought.

23:58.146 --> 24:00.732
I am simply trying to do my duty
as Colonel's wife...

24:00.815 --> 24:03.902
If you want to do it, just go ahead.
You don't need my permission.

24:03.985 --> 24:06.988
We both know the women
won't join if you don't.

24:07.238 --> 24:08.740
I'm quite aware
of how they feel about me.

24:10.658 --> 24:13.411
Listen, I know you still want
to be part of the gang.

24:13.495 --> 24:17.207
But unfortunately, you have
a leadership role on this tour.

24:17.290 --> 24:19.084
And that means responsibilities.

24:22.212 --> 24:23.922
You may not need the choir, Lisa.

24:24.255 --> 24:25.382
But those women do.

24:26.341 --> 24:28.635
<i>Blackbird has spoken</i>

24:28.718 --> 24:31.388
Can we at least call it
a singing club?

24:31.846 --> 24:33.890
How do people at Flitcroft
get involved?

24:33.973 --> 24:35.183
They just turn up.

24:35.475 --> 24:37.560
No auditions, everyone welcome.

24:37.852 --> 24:40.313
Yeah, so it's like a drop-in.

24:41.064 --> 24:42.774
Yeah, and then you commit.

24:42.857 --> 24:44.317
But only if you really want to.

24:45.944 --> 24:48.780
It's not about experience
or endless practice at home.

24:48.863 --> 24:50.240
<i>Though it'd be encouraged.</i>

24:50.323 --> 24:52.075
<i>So it's more about enthusiasm?</i>

24:52.158 --> 24:53.451
- <i>Well...</i>
- <i>Yes.</i>

24:53.535 --> 24:55.161
I know you're busy
but would you like...

24:55.954 --> 24:58.665
Just two hours, once a week.
Open to all ranks.

25:01.835 --> 25:04.421
Do you watch <i>Songs Of Praise?</i>
You might enjoy that.

25:05.797 --> 25:09.634
We're forming a choir. Would you
like to join? It's on Thursdays.

25:09.718 --> 25:11.177
<i>What kinds of songs will you sing?</i>

25:11.261 --> 25:12.262
<i>Pop music.</i>

25:12.345 --> 25:13.930
<i>Good old traditional and rousing.</i>

25:14.014 --> 25:15.140
<i>Rock.</i>

25:15.890 --> 25:18.309
- So it's gonna be like Sister Act?
- Yes.

25:18.393 --> 25:20.020
You know, without the Mafia hitmen.

25:20.520 --> 25:21.563
And the God bit.

25:23.023 --> 25:25.316
All right. I'll have a think.

25:25.400 --> 25:27.360
<i>It's open to all ranks, right?</i>

25:27.444 --> 25:29.070
Oh, yes, this choir is inclusive.

25:29.779 --> 25:32.907
Yeah, this singing club
is gonna be a lot of fun.

25:33.533 --> 25:34.784
And uplifting.

25:34.868 --> 25:37.829
Yeah, and there'll be
a few beers afterwards.

25:41.708 --> 25:43.543
<i>La-la-la-la-la</i>

25:43.626 --> 25:45.587
<i>La-la-la-la-la</i>

25:48.923 --> 25:51.926
That's lovely, a soprano. Little bit
flat, but we can work on that.

25:52.385 --> 25:54.971
- Who's next?
- I thought we didn't have to audition.

25:55.055 --> 25:58.058
This isn't an audition,
I'm just determining your vocal range.

25:59.476 --> 26:00.518
Anyone?

26:01.686 --> 26:03.563
- Oh?
- No.

26:03.646 --> 26:04.647
No?

26:04.731 --> 26:07.776
Why don't we just start off as a...
like, as a group?

26:07.859 --> 26:09.903
Yeah, OK. Feel free.

26:10.487 --> 26:12.197
- Yeah?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

26:12.947 --> 26:14.032
Erm...

26:14.699 --> 26:16.201
All right, everyone stand up.

26:16.493 --> 26:18.078
Everyone on your feet.

26:19.287 --> 26:20.288
Yeah?

26:21.039 --> 26:23.166
When you can't sing the note

26:23.708 --> 26:24.751
just sit down.

26:25.418 --> 26:28.046
It's OK, I'll do it.

26:29.506 --> 26:32.008
<i>La-la-la-la-la</i>

26:34.177 --> 26:36.346
<i>La-la-la-la-la</i>

26:38.515 --> 26:40.558
La-la-la-la-la

26:50.276 --> 26:51.736
Right, OK.

26:51.945 --> 26:55.115
Right, so everyone who's standing,
you're a soprano.

26:55.198 --> 26:57.242
So you just go to your left.

26:58.493 --> 27:01.287
That's your right. My left.

27:01.413 --> 27:03.415
And if you're still sitting down,
you're an alto.

27:03.498 --> 27:04.874
Go to the right.

27:04.958 --> 27:07.377
Ruby, I think
you're more of a minor tone.

27:07.752 --> 27:09.546
She just means your voice
is really powerful.

27:09.629 --> 27:11.214
- Yeah.
- You know...

27:11.506 --> 27:13.091
Imagine you're Luke Skywalker

27:13.174 --> 27:14.759
and you have to learn
to harness The Force.

27:16.720 --> 27:18.221
So where do the minors stand?

27:18.388 --> 27:19.597
- At the back.
- In the front.

27:20.807 --> 27:22.142
Erm... middle?

27:22.267 --> 27:23.435
Yeah.

27:24.978 --> 27:25.979
So...

27:27.439 --> 27:28.898
- You go ahead. No, no, go ahead.
- No...

27:29.107 --> 27:32.485
- OK...
- Thanks very much, Lisa. Lovely.

27:32.902 --> 27:36.740
So today's practice is going to focus
on something called count singing.

27:36.823 --> 27:38.116
Don't panic.

27:38.199 --> 27:39.951
It's a very easy exercise

27:40.035 --> 27:43.204
to help us with pitch and rhythm
without having to learn lyrics.

27:43.288 --> 27:44.998
Why don't we just sing a song?

27:45.123 --> 27:46.750
This is just how
I learnt it at school.

27:47.334 --> 27:48.335
So...

27:48.752 --> 27:51.004
<i>One, one, two, one</i>

27:51.087 --> 27:53.131
<i>One, two, three, two, one</i>

27:53.214 --> 27:55.925
<i>One, two, three,
four, three, two, one</i>

27:56.009 --> 27:58.303
See? It's very easy.
All together now.

27:59.095 --> 28:01.222
<i>One, one, two, one</i>

28:01.306 --> 28:03.558
<i>One, two, three,
four, three, two, one</i>

28:03.641 --> 28:05.352
<i>One, two, three, four, five...</i>

28:05.435 --> 28:08.021
No, sorry, there's no five. No five.

28:09.022 --> 28:10.190
We'll start again.

28:10.273 --> 28:13.318
<i>One, one, two, three, two, one</i>

28:13.401 --> 28:14.652
<i>One, two, one</i>

28:14.736 --> 28:16.654
<i>One, two, three,
four, three, two, one</i>

28:16.738 --> 28:17.781
<i>One, one, two, one...</i>

28:17.864 --> 28:19.240
- Bang!
- Oww!

28:20.075 --> 28:21.785
<i>One, two, three, two...</i>

28:27.207 --> 28:29.167
<i>Bum-bum, ba-ba-bum</i>

28:29.626 --> 28:30.669
<i>Ba-ba-ba...</i>

28:30.752 --> 28:32.170
- Does it not remind you of...
- No.

28:33.171 --> 28:35.674
<i>You were working
as a waitress in a...</i>

28:35.757 --> 28:37.175
<i>Cocktail bar</i>

28:37.258 --> 28:38.426
Does that...

28:38.718 --> 28:39.803
Shall we?

28:40.011 --> 28:41.846
<i>...when I met you</i>

28:42.305 --> 28:45.183
<i>I picked you up, I shook you off</i>

28:45.266 --> 28:47.477
<i>I turned you around</i>

28:47.560 --> 28:50.480
<i>I turned you into someone new</i>

28:50.563 --> 28:51.564
Come on, the chorus.

28:51.648 --> 28:53.692
<i>Don't... Don't...</i>

28:54.025 --> 28:55.610
<i>Don't you want me?</i>

28:56.152 --> 28:57.862
<i>You know I don't believe it</i>

28:58.113 --> 29:00.740
<i>When I hear that you won't see me</i>

29:00.824 --> 29:02.033
<i>Don't</i>

29:02.450 --> 29:03.993
<i>Don't you want me?</i>

29:05.036 --> 29:09.416
<i>You know I don't believe it
when I hear that you won't see me</i>

29:09.499 --> 29:11.418
<i>It's much too late to find</i>

29:11.501 --> 29:13.503
<i>That you think
you've changed your mind</i>

29:13.586 --> 29:18.216
<i>You'd better change it back
or we will both be sorry</i>

29:18.299 --> 29:20.677
<i>Don't you want me, baby?</i>

29:20.760 --> 29:22.554
<i>Boom-ba-doop, boo</i>

29:22.846 --> 29:26.433
<i>Don't you want me, oh-oh?</i>

29:26.766 --> 29:29.686
<i>Don't you want me, baby?</i>

29:29.769 --> 29:31.062
<i>Ba-da-ba-ba</i>

29:31.146 --> 29:34.733
<i>Don't you want me, oh-oh?</i>

29:35.233 --> 29:38.236
<i>Don't you want me, baby?</i>

29:39.571 --> 29:43.199
<i>Don't you want me, oh-oh?</i>

29:46.119 --> 29:47.162
Erm...

29:47.245 --> 29:48.872
I was just thinking
we could have a chat

29:48.955 --> 29:50.790
about how we're
gonna approach this.

29:51.166 --> 29:53.710
I wasn't aware
we were approaching anything.

29:53.960 --> 29:56.296
- I thought you asked for my help.
- To mobilise them.

29:56.504 --> 29:58.089
- I was thinking...
- Look.

29:58.506 --> 30:02.093
The point of choir isn't to facilitate
what the wives can already do.

30:02.177 --> 30:03.678
It's not sober karaoke.

30:04.012 --> 30:06.181
Choir needs to be challenging
so that for one hour,

30:06.264 --> 30:09.059
they're thinking about something
other than their troubles.

30:09.934 --> 30:11.644
We can't just muddle through.

30:11.728 --> 30:15.148
It needs to be organised, something
we both know is not your strongpoint.

30:17.192 --> 30:19.152
Can I have my pocket money?

30:19.235 --> 30:21.279
What? You've had it.

30:24.532 --> 30:26.618
You know, you could do something
to earn a bit of extra money.

30:26.701 --> 30:28.703
I'm not stacking shelves
in the NAAFI again.

30:28.787 --> 30:31.581
No, I mean, like, child-minding
for the singing club.

30:31.664 --> 30:33.249
- You could do that.
- I'm all right.

30:34.334 --> 30:36.169
Where are you going?
I'm about to make dinner.

30:36.252 --> 30:38.088
Nowhere. There is nowhere to go.

30:38.171 --> 30:41.466
- Well, what are you gonna eat?
- I might go to the chippy later.

30:41.758 --> 30:43.134
Oh, the chippy?

30:43.677 --> 30:45.512
Good job you've got
your leathers on.

30:45.595 --> 30:47.097
You know, and your full face.

30:47.305 --> 30:48.431
For the chippy.

30:55.355 --> 30:57.649
- I want change.
- Bye!

31:12.372 --> 31:14.290
One, two, three...

31:37.022 --> 31:38.356
Oh, my God.

32:24.527 --> 32:26.571
Hey, Kate, you're a soprano.

32:26.654 --> 32:27.989
Yeah, of course you are.

32:28.073 --> 32:30.492
Why don't you take a seat over
there beside Annie?

32:30.575 --> 32:32.410
We're not singing Yazoo?

32:32.494 --> 32:35.580
And don't get used to these.
I don't want you hiding behind them.

32:35.663 --> 32:37.540
- This is only the soprano part.
- Yeah.

32:37.624 --> 32:40.460
- I divide them up into parts.
- How do we know when to come in?

32:40.543 --> 32:43.505
I taught them.
They listened and they memorised.

32:43.588 --> 32:46.216
Oh. Are you going to play that thing
without any music?

32:46.800 --> 32:50.261
Yeah, I just think reading music
makes things a bit stilted.

32:50.345 --> 32:52.555
Oh, not sure Mozart
would agree with that.

32:52.639 --> 32:55.225
Well, The Beatles didn't read music
and I think they did OK.

32:55.308 --> 32:56.810
Yeah, OK.

32:57.018 --> 32:59.020
So we're gonna do
exactly what we did earlier.

32:59.104 --> 33:00.438
I'm gonna give you
your starting note.

33:04.901 --> 33:06.111
Three, four...

33:11.157 --> 33:14.035
<i>Looking from a window above</i>

33:14.119 --> 33:16.496
<i>It's like a story of love</i>

33:17.497 --> 33:20.500
<i>Can you hear me?</i>

33:20.959 --> 33:23.753
<i>Came back only yesterday</i>

33:23.837 --> 33:26.506
<i>I'm moving further away</i>

33:27.215 --> 33:29.884
<i>Want you near me</i>

33:29.968 --> 33:30.969
Yeah, OK.

33:31.052 --> 33:32.053
It was really good, so...

33:32.137 --> 33:36.891
May I suggest we just take a little
time just to learn the parts properly

33:36.975 --> 33:38.643
so that when
we add them all together...

33:38.727 --> 33:40.103
Everyone's lost the will to live.

33:41.271 --> 33:43.523
Let's just sing it again.
Just have one go, right?

33:43.606 --> 33:45.191
- OK, fine.
- Let's just go again.

33:45.734 --> 33:46.735
Absolutely.

33:49.112 --> 33:52.198
Sorry, but, my right hand
will show the tempo.

33:52.282 --> 33:54.576
One, two, three, four...

33:54.659 --> 33:57.954
And my left hand is going to
tell you when to come in. Like this.

33:58.038 --> 33:59.956
It's like she's guiding
a plane in to land.

34:00.040 --> 34:01.291
- Finished?
- Yeah.

34:01.374 --> 34:02.834
- And...
- Let's have a...

34:04.210 --> 34:06.296
One, two, three, four...

34:08.673 --> 34:11.718
<i>Looking from a window above</i>

34:11.801 --> 34:14.554
<i>It's like a story of love</i>

34:15.096 --> 34:18.391
<i>Can you hear me?</i>

34:18.850 --> 34:21.603
<i>Came back only yesterday</i>

34:21.686 --> 34:24.105
<i>I'm moving further away</i>

34:25.398 --> 34:28.360
<i>Want you near me</i>

34:29.486 --> 34:32.739
<i>All I needed was the love you gave</i>

34:34.449 --> 34:38.078
<i>All I needed for another day</i>

34:38.578 --> 34:42.123
<i>And all I ever knew</i>

34:42.665 --> 34:44.084
<i>Only you</i>

34:56.137 --> 34:57.806
We can't see you... There he is!

34:57.889 --> 34:59.808
- <i>Can you see me?</i>
- Say, "Hi, Daddy."

34:59.891 --> 35:02.477
- <i>Hey, Billy.</i>
- Hello, Daddy.

35:02.560 --> 35:04.688
- <i>Hey, mate.</i>
- Hello, Daddy.

35:05.397 --> 35:07.148
- <i>How are you?</i>
- Good.

35:07.232 --> 35:10.026
<i>What have you been doing, Billy?
Been a good boy for Mummy?</i>

35:10.694 --> 35:12.946
<i>Daddy misses you and Mummy
a million...</i>

35:13.738 --> 35:15.115
I miss you too. Are you there?

35:15.740 --> 35:16.741
Hello?

35:17.784 --> 35:19.661
We've lost you.
Hang on, are you there?

35:21.454 --> 35:22.455
Hello?

35:45.228 --> 35:46.354
Ah-ha.

36:20.889 --> 36:23.224
<i>The Ultimatt Air Bed
has a built-in pump</i>

36:23.391 --> 36:25.518
<i>and it can self-inflate
in just three minutes.</i>

36:25.602 --> 36:27.771
<i>Yeah, it's just so efficient.</i>

36:27.854 --> 36:30.231
<i>This bed can support
up to 200 kilograms.</i>

36:30.315 --> 36:32.525
<i>Suzy, you know
what weighs 200 kilograms?</i>

36:32.609 --> 36:34.027
<i>I don't know.
You tell me, Larry.</i>

36:34.110 --> 36:35.320
<i>This guy.</i>

36:35.403 --> 36:38.365
<i>Oh, my goodness!
Is that a gorilla?</i>

36:38.448 --> 36:39.532
<i>Get in here, fella.</i>

36:40.533 --> 36:43.536
<i>It's not a real gorilla, it's actually
a man in a gorilla suit</i>

36:43.620 --> 36:45.455
<i>and he has a weight
belt underneath.</i>

36:46.039 --> 36:47.665
<i>Quite some weight. OK, go.</i>

36:47.749 --> 36:49.876
<i>Oh, wow!</i>

36:54.005 --> 36:55.215
Ow!

37:00.804 --> 37:01.930
I can't...

37:04.349 --> 37:05.350
Frankie?

37:06.893 --> 37:09.646
- Are you all right?
- My stuff's all wet.

37:10.146 --> 37:11.147
I've got you.

37:11.231 --> 37:14.734
<i>Shout, shout, let it all out</i>

37:14.818 --> 37:16.319
<i>Let it all out</i>

37:16.903 --> 37:18.571
<i>Let it all out</i>

37:22.409 --> 37:25.662
<i>These are the things
I can do without</i>

37:25.745 --> 37:26.746
<i>Come on</i>

37:26.830 --> 37:28.540
Your mum's not answering.

37:28.623 --> 37:31.001
I've left a message,
I'm sure she'll be here in a minute.

37:31.084 --> 37:34.129
I'm not drunk, no. I only had one.

