54:42.782 --> 54:45.243
<i>I couldn't if I tried</i>

54:46.786 --> 54:49.706
<i>Well, honey, if I get restless...</i>

54:59.174 --> 55:01.509
<i>You took the weight off of me</i>

55:02.635 --> 55:05.805
<i>Oh, honey, knock...
Knock on my door</i>

55:06.514 --> 55:08.558
<i>Ooh, I gave you my key</i>

55:10.185 --> 55:12.145
<i>Ohhh...</i>

55:12.228 --> 55:13.772
<i>Ooh-hoo</i>

55:14.147 --> 55:16.149
<i>Nobody knows it</i>

55:23.615 --> 55:24.616
Hey.

55:25.367 --> 55:26.785
I wasn't trying to be pushy.

55:26.868 --> 55:29.079
No, no, no.
I just needed some air, that's all.

55:29.412 --> 55:31.956
Yeah, well, Kevin's singing
will do that to you.

55:41.883 --> 55:44.803
Jamie and I sang that song together
at his 18th.

55:46.262 --> 55:47.639
- Oh, fuck.
- Yeah.

55:50.058 --> 55:52.394
He made me. I was mortified.

55:52.477 --> 55:54.062
He, of course,
thought it was hilarious.

55:57.232 --> 55:59.442
But then, he thought
his job on this earth

55:59.526 --> 56:01.027
was to keep people laughing.

56:06.533 --> 56:09.869
Yeah, I remember Red saying that
he had a way of looking at things...

56:10.745 --> 56:12.539
he'd just find the funny
in everything.

56:15.083 --> 56:16.376
Even when he was little.

56:17.085 --> 56:20.296
Whenever Richard went away,
we'd have this big jar of sweets,

56:20.380 --> 56:23.425
and Jamie was allowed one sweet
a day every day of the tour.

56:23.967 --> 56:26.261
And when the jar
was empty, Richard...

56:27.220 --> 56:28.263
Frankie did that.

56:28.847 --> 56:31.599
Counting down the days till the
family was back together again.

56:32.350 --> 56:35.353
Jamie used to say,
"Until we laugh again."

56:38.815 --> 56:40.442
Mm.

56:42.402 --> 56:43.987
- That's so sweet.
- Yeah.

56:48.491 --> 56:50.035
I don't know how you...

56:55.582 --> 56:57.083
Oh.

56:57.917 --> 56:59.169
Right, OK.

56:59.252 --> 57:00.628
I'm off.

57:00.712 --> 57:02.714
You don't have to.
I'm not gonna make you sing.

57:03.006 --> 57:04.049
Good night.

57:05.300 --> 57:06.384
Hey, Kate?

57:06.968 --> 57:08.053
The Albert Hall, huh?

57:08.720 --> 57:11.056
Not tall poppies any more,
we're bloody sunflowers.

57:13.266 --> 57:14.267
Night.

57:16.895 --> 57:18.313
<i>If you wanna be my lover</i>

57:20.398 --> 57:22.692
<i>Slam, slam, slam, slam!</i>

57:22.901 --> 57:24.778
<i>If you wanna be my lover...</i>

57:24.861 --> 57:26.571
<i>Slam your body down
and wind it all around</i>

57:26.654 --> 57:28.406
<i>Hup, hup, hup, hup!</i>

57:43.922 --> 57:46.091
- Tell me.
- <i>Comms are down.</i>

57:46.466 --> 57:49.094
<i>Richard's been injured
but he's gonna be OK.</i>

57:49.219 --> 57:50.637
<i>He's in Kabul hospital.</i>

57:50.970 --> 57:53.556
<i>RAMC will fly him back later today,</i>

57:53.640 --> 57:55.558
<i>transfer him straight to Flitcroft.</i>

57:55.642 --> 57:56.810
Any fatalities?

57:58.353 --> 57:59.354
Handball.

58:00.021 --> 58:01.106
You handballed that.

58:03.775 --> 58:05.360
Skills. Go on.

58:07.028 --> 58:08.279
Gotcha. Ready?

58:17.580 --> 58:18.748
Pass me the ball.

58:19.541 --> 58:20.750
Come on, pass me the ball.

58:22.127 --> 58:23.753
Let's go and get a little biccy
or something, eh?

58:24.337 --> 58:25.463
All right?

58:29.092 --> 58:30.760
- Any pink ones?
- Yeah.

58:41.104 --> 58:43.064
Sarah Cartwright?

58:53.992 --> 58:55.243
Who is her trusted friend?

58:55.827 --> 58:59.205
She didn't name anyone. Said she was
waiting to see who she got close to.

59:02.959 --> 59:06.838
Well, Jess is
good at stuff like that. Or Ruby.

59:07.672 --> 59:08.798
She's asked for you, Kate.

59:10.300 --> 59:11.509
Says you've been there yourself.

59:26.107 --> 59:27.192
OK.

59:40.705 --> 59:41.790
It's fallen over.

59:43.333 --> 59:44.501
Sorry?

59:45.251 --> 59:46.753
Liam's teddy's fallen over.

59:48.755 --> 59:50.256
That doesn't mean anything.

59:51.424 --> 59:53.551
Of course it does,
because what it means has happened.

1:00:03.228 --> 1:00:04.229
Here.

1:00:06.272 --> 1:00:07.315
Thanks.

1:00:18.076 --> 1:00:19.452
Do I have to leave the base now?

1:00:20.537 --> 1:00:23.164
No. No, whenever you're ready.

1:00:25.333 --> 1:00:26.668
But don't think about that now.

1:00:52.527 --> 1:00:53.528
Right, so...

1:00:54.529 --> 1:00:55.613
shall we give it a go?

1:00:59.534 --> 1:01:01.911
Do you think she's read
Liam's death letter yet?

1:01:04.372 --> 1:01:06.458
I don't think I could read Stu's
if it came to it.

1:01:09.294 --> 1:01:10.503
I read Malc's...

1:01:12.547 --> 1:01:14.257
after the last Afghan tour.

1:01:16.634 --> 1:01:17.719
I'd do it again.

1:01:20.138 --> 1:01:21.431
It helped me. It said...

1:01:23.767 --> 1:01:26.853
all these lovely things about me
that he'd never say to my face.

1:01:30.774 --> 1:01:33.943
To be fair, though, he's not gonna
not write that, is he?

1:01:36.196 --> 1:01:38.656
I mean, he's not gonna write
a list of things he hates about you.

1:01:41.493 --> 1:01:45.163
"Dear Ruby, wish you'd rinse the
bath out after you shave your legs."

1:01:47.332 --> 1:01:48.375
"Dear Jess,

1:01:48.458 --> 1:01:51.586
"really wish you wouldn't wash up
the cups before I'd finished my tea."

1:01:51.670 --> 1:01:54.422
I wish you wouldn't do that,
to be honest. It's so annoying.

1:01:55.298 --> 1:01:57.842
I just can't bear
the thought of anyone

1:01:57.926 --> 1:02:00.261
coming to give me bad news
and the house being a mess.

1:02:05.809 --> 1:02:08.228
I'm not in
the mood for singing today.

1:02:30.875 --> 1:02:31.960
Darling.

1:02:34.129 --> 1:02:36.464
This is nothing serious.

1:02:39.509 --> 1:02:41.720
- You're lucky.
- I was stupid.

1:02:41.803 --> 1:02:42.929
Mm.

1:02:45.098 --> 1:02:46.891
Katy, there's something
I need to tell you.

1:02:48.351 --> 1:02:49.394
No, you don't.

1:02:50.520 --> 1:02:51.813
- I don't?
- No.

1:02:53.273 --> 1:02:54.524
I know you didn't have to go.

1:02:55.442 --> 1:02:56.609
You put yourself forward.

1:03:00.739 --> 1:03:05.618
You try and file away those feelings
about what happened

1:03:05.702 --> 1:03:07.495
on the shelves in your head.

1:03:12.542 --> 1:03:13.710
I shouldn't have gone.

1:03:19.674 --> 1:03:22.510
Richard, sorry, I've got so many
things to do, I've got to leave.

1:03:22.594 --> 1:03:23.720
Call you later.

1:03:23.803 --> 1:03:26.681
It's the thing I admire
about you most, the way you cope.

1:03:29.309 --> 1:03:31.353
That is a depressing thing to say,
Richard.

1:03:31.436 --> 1:03:33.104
Are you going to put that
on my gravestone?

1:03:33.188 --> 1:03:36.316
I meant I understand how you feel.

1:03:36.399 --> 1:03:39.527
Oh, you understand?
What do you understand, exactly?

1:03:40.153 --> 1:03:42.280
- Enlighten me.
- No, I just...

1:03:42.364 --> 1:03:44.407
I'm the one who has
to answer the phone in the night,

1:03:44.491 --> 1:03:46.534
who has to worry about
what state you'll come back in,

1:03:46.618 --> 1:03:49.996
who has to...
who has to look at you in that bed

1:03:50.080 --> 1:03:53.083
and then I have to go out there,
I have to get on with it

1:03:53.166 --> 1:03:54.334
and do my duty.

1:03:54.417 --> 1:03:57.253
I have responsibilities,
I can't go round with a wet face.

1:03:57.671 --> 1:04:01.591
"I'm so sorry, my husband's been blown up.
Would you like a cup of tea?

1:04:01.883 --> 1:04:04.469
"I'm so sorry, my husband's
got shrapnel in his head.

1:04:04.594 --> 1:04:05.595
"Have some cake."

1:04:05.679 --> 1:04:08.264
I've always said you should be paid
for what you do.

1:04:35.208 --> 1:04:38.920
Lisa, I can't come to practice now.
I'm at the hospital with Richard.

1:04:39.004 --> 1:04:40.046
How is he?

1:04:40.839 --> 1:04:43.633
- <i>He's fine.</i>
- OK. Good.

1:04:43.717 --> 1:04:46.678
- What's the matter?
- No, I just wanted to, erm...

1:04:47.178 --> 1:04:49.806
let you know that you don't need
to worry about the Albert Hall.

1:04:49.889 --> 1:04:51.599
<i>The women don't want
to do it any more.</i>

1:04:52.017 --> 1:04:54.144
- It's a bit late for that.
- I'm sorry?

1:04:54.227 --> 1:04:57.063
It's utterly inappropriate
to pull out now.

1:04:57.147 --> 1:05:00.025
Well, they feel it would be utterly
inappropriate for them to sing.

1:05:00.150 --> 1:05:02.110
Lisa, if we pull out now,

1:05:02.277 --> 1:05:04.654
it will reflect badly on all of us.

1:05:06.156 --> 1:05:07.407
Shit.

1:05:18.209 --> 1:05:20.170
There will be a service
at Camp Bastion.

1:05:21.755 --> 1:05:23.631
Then Liam's body will be repatriated

1:05:23.715 --> 1:05:26.634
on a C-17 aircraft
coming through Wootton Bassett.

1:05:29.804 --> 1:05:33.308
After that, you and his parents are
going to have to make some decisions.

1:05:34.351 --> 1:05:37.187
Well, he grew up in care.
It's just me and the Army.

1:05:39.689 --> 1:05:40.857
And he...

1:05:40.940 --> 1:05:43.026
Did he ever express any wishes?

1:05:45.445 --> 1:05:46.821
No? OK.

1:05:48.823 --> 1:05:51.826
Well, then, we have to decide
what you want,

1:05:51.910 --> 1:05:54.954
whether you want a cremation
or a burial...

1:05:55.997 --> 1:05:57.499
flowers and a reading...

1:06:03.546 --> 1:06:04.589
What did you do?

1:06:06.466 --> 1:06:08.051
Oh, erm...

1:06:09.344 --> 1:06:10.887
James had a willow coffin.

1:06:12.472 --> 1:06:14.057
Are they the ones
where there's no lid

1:06:14.140 --> 1:06:16.351
and the bodies are covered
with flowers?

1:06:16.434 --> 1:06:18.937
You can do, but Jamie needed a lid.

1:06:23.900 --> 1:06:25.902
Liam's gonna need a lid as well,
isn't he?

1:06:29.364 --> 1:06:31.491
Shall I get that?

1:06:31.574 --> 1:06:32.701
It's OK.

1:06:34.285 --> 1:06:35.453
Right.

1:06:42.168 --> 1:06:43.211
Guys.

1:06:43.920 --> 1:06:45.171
Oh, come in, come in. Come in.

1:06:56.683 --> 1:06:57.684
Guys?

1:06:58.143 --> 1:06:59.352
OK.

1:06:59.936 --> 1:07:01.187
Sorry, could I...

1:07:02.230 --> 1:07:05.567
Could I just play you something
and ask you a question?

1:07:08.153 --> 1:07:12.907
So I first met Liam when he
was put next to me in English.

1:07:13.241 --> 1:07:15.160
He was dead naughty
and I was always a bit of a swat.

1:07:15.243 --> 1:07:17.078
They thought I'd sort him out.

1:07:18.496 --> 1:07:21.541
But our teacher took us on a trip
to York Cathedral.

1:07:22.000 --> 1:07:23.960
And there was a
choir practising this.

1:07:24.419 --> 1:07:27.589
Liam hated classical music.
He preferred grime.

1:07:27.672 --> 1:07:30.175
But he
did always like this.

1:07:31.134 --> 1:07:32.135
This one.

1:07:33.595 --> 1:07:36.890
And he sat next to me to listen to it.

1:07:36.973 --> 1:07:39.768
And while it was playing,
he touched my hand.

1:07:40.852 --> 1:07:43.855
And I remember nothing
about the rest of the concert,

1:07:43.938 --> 1:07:45.523
I was too busy thinking
about his hand.

1:07:48.902 --> 1:07:53.281
So that is how I'd really like to feel
when I say bye to him.

1:07:55.658 --> 1:07:59.204
You know, I want to feel
his hand touching mine.

1:08:00.330 --> 1:08:02.415
So I'd really, really love it if...

1:08:03.750 --> 1:08:07.962
if you could sing this for me,
well, for him, at his service.

1:08:31.361 --> 1:08:38.243
<i>Maiden mild</i>

1:08:40.620 --> 1:08:47.585
<i>O, listen to a maiden's prayer</i>

1:08:50.880 --> 1:08:57.804
<i>For Thou canst hear amid the wild</i>

1:09:00.390 --> 1:09:03.309
<i>'Tis Thou</i>

1:09:03.601 --> 1:09:10.567
<i>'Tis Thou canst save amid despair</i>

1:09:13.028 --> 1:09:14.487
Fire!

1:09:18.158 --> 1:09:19.409
Load!

1:09:23.788 --> 1:09:25.290
Fire!

1:09:25.373 --> 1:09:27.959
- It was a beautiful service.
- Thank you.

1:09:28.960 --> 1:09:29.961
Kate.

1:09:31.087 --> 1:09:32.213
It's been far too long.

1:09:33.214 --> 1:09:36.343
I'm really looking forward
to the full choir performance

1:09:36.426 --> 1:09:37.719
at the Festival of Remembrance.

1:09:37.802 --> 1:09:40.096
Yes, but sadly
we're not going to do it.

1:09:40.305 --> 1:09:41.389
What?

1:09:41.473 --> 1:09:44.642
Yes, the women have decided
that it's just too soon.

1:09:52.484 --> 1:09:53.860
You're not doing the Albert Hall?

1:09:54.819 --> 1:09:55.820
Well...

1:09:56.696 --> 1:09:59.032
You sang today and it was beautiful.

1:09:59.115 --> 1:10:00.325
But that was just for you today,

1:10:00.408 --> 1:10:02.077
it was personal,
not for entertainment.

1:10:02.660 --> 1:10:04.579
Guys, make
it personal, then.

1:10:05.622 --> 1:10:06.748
Please don't pull out.

1:10:08.625 --> 1:10:11.127
There are gonna be
so many people in that room...

1:10:12.087 --> 1:10:13.254
like me.

1:10:15.215 --> 1:10:16.883
And I want to do this for them.

1:10:17.676 --> 1:10:19.552
But I can't do that on my own.

1:10:23.056 --> 1:10:25.642
- What are we gonna sing?
- Does it have to be classical?

1:10:26.059 --> 1:10:27.268
Dunno.

1:10:28.103 --> 1:10:30.563
Maybe we should do <i>Angels,</i>
like at Sarah's wedding.

1:10:30.980 --> 1:10:32.524
It's not really about us,
though, is it?

1:10:33.066 --> 1:10:35.110
We're not gonna find anything
that's about us, though.

1:10:36.152 --> 1:10:37.862
Know what song
I've always really liked?

1:10:37.987 --> 1:10:39.698
That Dido one where she goes,

1:10:39.781 --> 1:10:42.617
"I woke up, my tea's cold,
I've got a hangover

1:10:42.701 --> 1:10:43.827
"but you've made everything great."

1:10:43.910 --> 1:10:44.953
That classic!

1:10:45.036 --> 1:10:47.122
It is a classic, it's really personal.

1:10:47.205 --> 1:10:50.208
<i>My tea's gone cold,
I'm wondering why</i>

1:10:50.417 --> 1:10:52.711
<i>I got out of bed at all</i>

1:10:52.794 --> 1:10:56.214
<i>The morning rain
clouds on my window</i>

1:10:56.381 --> 1:10:58.550
<i>And I can't see at all</i>

1:10:58.758 --> 1:11:02.220
And then Eminem, don't say it,
starts rapping about a psychotic stalker.

1:11:03.096 --> 1:11:04.973
Love that at the Royal Albert Hall.

1:11:05.056 --> 1:11:07.017
Maz could do that bit. Bit of rapping.

1:11:07.100 --> 1:11:08.893
- I forgot about that bit.
- Maz and a rap.

1:11:11.104 --> 1:11:12.188
Let's, er...

1:11:13.148 --> 1:11:14.482
Let's just keep thinking, yeah?

1:11:14.691 --> 1:11:16.192
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

1:11:16.609 --> 1:11:18.862
- All right.
- Night. Have a good night.

1:11:32.542 --> 1:11:34.336
<i>Yeah!</i>

1:11:45.472 --> 1:11:47.015
Oh, you have a bluey from Dad.

1:11:48.475 --> 1:11:49.517
Right.

1:12:10.580 --> 1:12:11.790
Do you want to watch a film?

1:12:14.000 --> 1:12:15.001
A film.

1:12:16.586 --> 1:12:17.629
Oh.

1:12:18.963 --> 1:12:19.964
Yeah.

1:12:20.048 --> 1:12:21.758
- Yeah.
- What do you fancy?

1:12:24.386 --> 1:12:25.387
I will have a look.

1:12:33.353 --> 1:12:34.354
<i>Rocky?</i>

1:12:36.272 --> 1:12:38.233
What? Are you serious?

1:12:38.316 --> 1:12:39.317
Yeah.

1:12:39.818 --> 1:12:41.486
- OK, fine.
- Yes, yes!

1:12:45.615 --> 1:12:47.033
<i>That's a good idea, Lisa.</i>

1:12:47.409 --> 1:12:50.412
But the thing is,
all my letters are about QPR.

1:12:51.621 --> 1:12:54.374
Mine are far too mucky.

1:12:55.166 --> 1:12:57.502
We won't put any of the dirty bits in.
We'll just...

1:12:58.169 --> 1:13:01.256
you know, find bits
that represent our feelings

1:13:01.339 --> 1:13:02.966
and just work it into the song.

1:13:03.174 --> 1:13:04.300
Just like that?

1:13:04.384 --> 1:13:06.886
I'm not expecting
to win a Brit Award.

1:13:06.970 --> 1:13:08.179
But how bad can it be?

1:13:08.263 --> 1:13:10.432
You've not read what I've written.

1:13:10.515 --> 1:13:14.019
It's not gonna be all, "I love you
to the moon and back" is it?

1:13:14.978 --> 1:13:16.896
I don't want to puke down myself
in the Albert Hall.

1:13:16.980 --> 1:13:20.275
You don't want me to make us
look like meek little women

1:13:20.358 --> 1:13:21.818
pining for our big brave husbands?

1:13:21.901 --> 1:13:23.236
And wives.

1:13:23.319 --> 1:13:25.989
What's wrong with saying,
"I love you to the moon and back"?

1:13:26.740 --> 1:13:29.534
There's nothing wrong
with it at all, Jess.

1:13:29.617 --> 1:13:30.869
It's just a little bit...

1:13:30.952 --> 1:13:32.954
- Sorry.
- Kate?

1:13:33.955 --> 1:13:36.041
Lisa's got an idea
for the Albert Hall.

1:13:36.124 --> 1:13:37.125
Oh, good.

1:13:37.625 --> 1:13:40.420
I was just thinking about
what Sarah was saying...

1:13:40.545 --> 1:13:43.673
about making the
song more personal.

1:13:44.382 --> 1:13:45.550
We're gonna write our own song.

1:13:46.634 --> 1:13:48.094
- Using bits of our letters.
- Yeah.

1:13:48.178 --> 1:13:49.971
And putting
them to Lisa's tune.

1:13:51.139 --> 1:13:52.140
Oh.

1:13:52.724 --> 1:13:54.768
- Play your song for her.
- Go on, play it.

1:13:55.101 --> 1:13:57.395
It's not a song yet. It's just...

1:13:58.438 --> 1:14:00.190
It's a... You know, it's like a...

1:14:02.233 --> 1:14:05.278
It's a tune.
You have to imagine the words bit.

1:14:13.578 --> 1:14:15.288
Actually, do you think
we could talk about this later?

1:14:18.124 --> 1:14:20.460
Well, why don't we talk about it
now? Everyone's here.

1:14:22.253 --> 1:14:25.674
Really, how realistic is this,
given your limitations?

1:14:26.383 --> 1:14:29.177
- What?
- You can't read music, can you?

1:14:30.303 --> 1:14:34.015
The Festival of Remembrance
is a professional event.

1:14:34.099 --> 1:14:37.977
It's not some amateur
school choir performance.

1:14:38.228 --> 1:14:41.147
We cannot embarrass ourselves
and we cannot let Flitcroft down.

1:14:41.231 --> 1:14:42.357
Do you know what? Forget it.

1:14:44.567 --> 1:14:45.944
Let's go back to the song board.

1:14:47.445 --> 1:14:48.488
Come on.

1:14:49.447 --> 1:14:50.907
I think we should
write our own song.

1:14:52.075 --> 1:14:53.076
Lisa, go on.

1:14:53.493 --> 1:14:55.662
And even if it's not amazing,
